She performed as a guitarist and vocalist for the group's 2014 studio album The River and the Willow, having previously appeared on their self-released 2011 debut West Simcoe County.

Through indie music label, Sonic Unyon, Lightfoot released her first solo album, self-titled and released in 2011, was described as "subdued", with compositions characteristic of a modern folk singer-songwriter.
Her second solo album,  2014's Every Time My Mind Runs Wild, saw her collaborate with indie rockers Gus van Go, Werner F, and Liam O'Neil (known for his performances with the group The Stills).
In 2017, Terra Lightfoot released two new albums.
The album's single "Paradise" also earned producer van Go a 2018 JUNO nomination for Recording Engineer of the Year, as well as a long-list nomination for the 2018 Polaris Music Prize.
In August 2020, Lightfoot released a new single, "Paper Thin Walls," from her fourth studio album, Consider the Speed.
That album was released on October 16, 2020.
March 2018 Lightfoot was featured in Guitar Player Magazine along with her SG 'Veronica'.
In 2017 she was honoured by the Canadian Independent Music Association for being a touring musician selling at least 25,000 concert seats in a 12-month period.
While touring her 2017 album New Mistakes, Lightfoot also created, curated, and co-headlined The Longest Road Show, an all-female touring revue.
Terra Lightfoot (2011)
Every Time My Mind Runs Wild (2015)
New Mistakes (2017)
Consider the Speed (October 16, 2020)
Live in Concert (2017)
New Mistakes earned Lightfoot a nomination for a 2018 JUNO Award for Adult Alternative Album of the Year.
She supported Willie Nelson on the lone Canadian date of the 2018 Outlaw Music Festival.
In the early 2010s Lightfoot was a member of the Dinner Belles, a group of country-folk performers from Hamilton.
She performed as a guitarist and vocalist for the group's 2014 studio album The River and the Willow, having previously appeared on their self-released 2011 debut West Simcoe County.
In February she released orchestral collaboration Live in Concert.
In late summer, Lightfoot released "Paradise," the lead single from her third studio album, New Mistakes.
The album's single "Paradise" also earned producer van Go a 2018 JUNO nomination for Recording Engineer of the Year, as well as a long-list nomination for the 2018 Polaris Music Prize.
Lightfoot has a multi-octave mezzo-soprano singing voice that has been compared to that of Joan Jett and Dusty Springfield.
On tour, Lightfoot has collaborated with a famous Canadian singer forty years her senior, Gordon Lightfoot, though the two are not related.
